The Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) issued an emergency airworthiness directive on the 24th, requiring an emergency inspection of about 2,000 Boeing 737NG and 737Classic passenger aircraft registered in the United States, because the corrosion of the air check valve of the above-mentioned passenger aircraft may cause the engine to stop in the air.
The FAA said that so far, it has received four reports of engine parking in the air of 737NG and 737Classic passenger aircraft, so it has made an emergency inspection request. The inspection targets are passenger aircraft that have been parked continuously for 7 days or more and passenger aircraft that have flown less than 11 times so far after re-entering flight.
The FAA warned that if the stage 5 check valves of all two engines of the airliner were corroded, they could get stuck in the open position, causing the airliner to lose power completely and be unable to restart the engine.
The aviation regulator ordered that if the check valve is found to be corroded, the airline operator must replace this key component before the airliner is put into use again.
Boeing responded later in the day that the outbreak of the COVID-19 epidemic led to reduced travel demand, so many passenger planes were sealed or less used, and " check valves were more vulnerable to corrosion. "
Boeing also said that it has advised air operators to inspect the passenger aircraft involved in the directive. If problems are found, Boeing will provide assistance in repairing and replacing check valves.
The Associated Press reported that passenger planes owned by major US airline operators usually fly many times a day, but after the outbreak of the COVID-19 epidemic, a large number of passenger planes have been grounded; with the recent slow growth of passenger travel demand, some passenger planes have returned to operation.
The FAA did not release details of the four air parking reports.
Alaska Airlines disclosed one of the incidents later on the 24th.
The airline operator said in a statement that on July 15, one of its passenger planes was flying from Seattle, Washington, to Austin, Texas, when an engine suddenly shut down, and the passenger plane finally made an emergency landing at Austin Airport.
Alaska Airlines said it had replaced the engine of the airliner and had inspected the engines of six airliners in accordance with FAA instructions.
American Airlines, United Airlines and Southwest Airlines said on the 24th that their airliners had no engine failure related to the air check valve.
Four American Airlines passenger planes will be inspected, and 28 United Airlines passenger planes will be inspected.
Delta Air Lines said it would inspect its 20 airliners, but did not say whether there had been engine failure.
According to several media reports, the FAA emergency airworthiness directive is another impact on Boeing.
A Boeing 737MAX of Lion Air Indonesia and Ethiopian Airlines crashed in October 2018 and March 2019 respectively, killing a total of 346 people.
This series of passenger planes were subsequently grounded worldwide, stopped production in January this year, and resumed production in May.
FAA Director Steve Dixon admitted in June that the FAA had " made a mistake " in regulating Boeing with regard to the 737MAX.
