Kao Xili Tibetan antelope enters the migration season-Xinhuanet
Xinhua News Agency, Xining, July 25 (Reporter Wang Jinjin) The reporter learned from the Wudaoliang Protection Station of the Kaoxili Management Office of the Yangtze River Source Park of the Sanjiangyuan National Park Administration that the monitoring showed that the Tibetan antelopes who had previously migrated to the Zhuonai Lake area in the hinterland of Kaoxili were ending giving birth and began to return to their original habitat with their young.
Surveillance footage near Wudaoliang Protection Station shows that on July 25, about 40 female Tibetan antelopes led three Tibetan antelope cubs through 3002 kilometers of Qinghai-Tibet Highway and Wudaoliang North Bridge of Qinghai-Tibet Railway. Tibetan antelopes have begun to move back.
According to expert analysis, in recent years, the number of Tibetan antelope cubs in the returning sheep accounted for one-quarter to one-fifth of the total number of Tibetan antelopes.
Lian Xinming, an associate researcher at the Northwest Plateau Institute of Biology of the Chinese Academy of Sciences, said: " In the early stage of migration, the Tibetan antelope faces a higher risk of predation, so the number of cubs in the sheep will be relatively small, and there may even be no cubs. "
According to the statistics of the Kao Xili Management Office of the Yangtze River Source Park of the Sanjiangyuan National Park Administration, the number of Tibetan antelopes returning is generally increasing year by year. In 2019, the number of Tibetan antelopes returning was 4,860, an increase of 338 over 2018.
Lian Xinming said: " It is expected that the migration of Tibetan antelopes this year will end in early September, and the number of Tibetan antelopes is still expected to continue to increase. "
The Tibetan antelope is a national-level protected animal.
At the end of May every year, Tibetan antelopes from Sanjiangyuan in Qinghai, Qiangtang in Tibet, Aljinshan in Xinjiang and other places go to Zhuonai Lake in the hinterland of Koxili to give birth.
Wu Xiaomin, a Tibetan antelope protection expert in China and a researcher at the Shaanxi Provincial Institute of Zoology (Northwest Institute of Endangered Animals), said: " The migration of Tibetan antelopes is a process in which female Tibetan antelopes return to their habitat with their cubs after giving birth. At first, the migration group leaving the breeding site is relatively large, but then Tibetan antelopes will return to their respective habitats according to different geographical populations and along different paths. "
In order to ensure the safe relocation of Tibetan antelopes, the reporter learned that the Kaoxili Management Office of the Yangtze River Source Park of the Sanjiangyuan National Park Administration has arranged staff to continuously carry out video monitoring and district patrols in the main relocation areas.
If a herd of Tibetan antelopes is found trying to cross the road, the mountain patrol team will carry out temporary traffic control at the first time to let the sheep safely pass through the wildlife passage to ensure that they are as little disturbed by human beings as possible on the way back.
