Brazilian study shows that hydroxychloroquine is ineffective in the treatment of mild and moderate COVID-19 pneumonia-Chinanews.com
Recently, a Brazilian study showed that hydroxychloroquine was ineffective in patients with mild to moderate COVID-19 pneumonia.
The study was published in the New England Journal of Medicine.
Pakistani researchers divided 667 patients from 55 hospitals across the country into three groups and conducted clinical trials; mainly compared the therapeutic effects of hydroxychloroquine alone or in combination with other antibiotics azithromycin, and analyzed whether it helped to improve the condition of mild and moderate patients with COVID-19 pneumonia.
The results show that hydroxychloroquine not only has no therapeutic effect, but may have damaging side effects on organs.
The study was carried out by a number of authoritative Brazilian hospitals such as Hospital Israel Albert Einstein, Cardiology Hospital (HCor), Hospital Sírio-Libanês, etc., in conjunction with the Brazilian Clinical Institute (BCRI) and the Brazilian Intensive Care Research Network (BRICNet).
On the 25th local time, Brazilian President Bosonaro announced through social platforms that the fourth nucleic acid test result was negative.
During the infection, Bosonaro has been taking hydroxychloroquine and actively promoting it many times.
