Hao Yusheng, chief representative of NASDAQ Stock Exchange in China, said at the " 2020 Listed Company Leaders Summit " hosted by Snowball.
In April this year, the US Securities and Futures Commission (SEC) and the US Public Company Accounting Oversight Board (PCAOB) issued the " Statement on the Important Role of Audit Quality and Regulation in Obtaining Audit and Other International Information-A Discussion on the Current Challenges of Information Access for US Listed Companies with a Large Business in China. "
The statement said that although international cooperation and coordination have increased significantly in recent years, the problems of US regulators in obtaining information still exist, and the SEC and PCAOB still face legal and practical challenges. Corresponding to the document, the PCAOB website lists in detail the list of listed companies and their audit institutions that have encountered audit obstacles, and a large number of Chinese stock companies are listed.
In addition, in May this year, the US Senate passed the Foreign Company Accountability Act, which introduced additional information disclosure requirements for foreign companies to list in the United States.
In Hao Yusheng's view, the Zhongbao stock crisis did not affect the appetite of investors.
" When this news first came out, it caused everyone's panic. Everyone was asking if they could go public in the United States in the future, but later we found that these questions were not a matter for investors. Investors may ask these questions during the recent IPO roadshow in the United States, or even become standardized questions, but this has not been regarded by investors as an important factor in investing in or not investing in a Chinese company.
It is suggested that everyone try to view the current situation with a normal mind.
Of course, this may appear to be the most serious situation in the past two years, but in terms of investors' appetite, it has not been affected in any way.
So the upsurge of IPOs in the United States will continue from now until the end of this year or before the US election. "
On May 9 this year, Jinshan Cloud officially listed on NASDAQ in the United States, becoming the first Chinese enterprise to go to the United States for an IPO after the epidemic.
" The listing of Jinshan Cloud gives great confidence to the Chinese companies that are preparing for IPO. "
Hao Yusheng said.
The data report on Chinese stocks in the first half of 2020 released by Snowball shows that in the first half of this year, a total of 20 Chinese enterprises went to the United States for IPOs, an increase of 17.6% over the same period last year; In terms of the total initial fund-raising, 20 enterprises raised a total of 2.725 billion yuan, an increase of more than 52.4% compared with the same period last year; In terms of industry distribution, the number of IPOs in the health care industry in the first half of this year was outstanding, an increase of 100% over the same period last year.
According to Hao Yusheng, the Chinese companies that went to the United States for IPO in the first half of this year are of high quality, and high-quality companies with strong fundamentals and growth will be more favored by investors.
In the short, medium and long term, Hao Yusheng continues to be optimistic about Ming China's IPO in the United States.
" In the short term, the upsurge of IPO in the United States continues; in the medium term, Chinese companies have more choices, A-shares, Hong Kong stocks and US stocks, and everyone will take the US election and Sino-US relations as market choices and timing considerations; In the long run, everything will return to normal, and market fluctuations are cycles, both political and economic, and will eventually return to the normal stage. The stock market has always been volatile. "
Hao Yusheng also said, " There are many uncertain factors this year, but for high-quality companies, whether the market is good or bad, as long as they are solid and have growth that investors can see, other factors are relatively secondary. Investors need to invest in excellent Chinese companies. "
