APEC member trade ministers said they will accelerate regional economic recovery-Xinhuanet
Xinhua News Agency, Kuala Lumpur, July 25 (Reporter Lin Hao) The video conference of trade ministers of APEC members was held on the 25th. The meeting pledged to work to reduce the impact of the COVID-19 epidemic on the regional economy and accelerate the realization of a resilient, sustainable and inclusive regional economic recovery.
The meeting was hosted by Malaysia, the host of this year's APEC Economic Leaders' Meeting.
The joint statement issued after the meeting said that the trade ministers of APEC members recognized the importance of a free, open, fair, non-discriminatory, transparent and predictable trade and investment environment to promote economic recovery at this challenging time.
All parties undertake to ensure that the emergency measures taken to deal with the epidemic are targeted, appropriate, transparent and temporary, do not create unnecessary trade barriers and disrupt global supply chains, and abide by the rules of the World Trade Organization.
In the statement, the trade ministers of APEC members pledged to strengthen cooperation to promote the flow of necessary goods and services, promote connectivity by strengthening supply chain flexibility, and minimize interference in the flow of medical supplies, food and agricultural products in order to deal with the epidemic.
The trade ministers of APEC members agreed that it is necessary to discuss how to reduce non-tariff barriers that restrict the trade of necessary goods, and reiterated their commitment to promoting the necessary cross-border movement of people without affecting the measures taken to stop the spread of the epidemic.
The meeting also issued a declaration on promoting the circulation of necessary commodities.
The declaration stated that all economies will ensure that the trade measures they take in response to the epidemic are in line with WTO regulations, and pledged to take actions in reducing non-tariff trade barriers and trade promotion to promote the necessary commodity flow under the epidemic.
Azmin Ali, Minister of International Trade and Industry of Malaysia, who chaired the meeting, said that despite the impact of the epidemic, Malaysia is still committed to promoting the success of this year's APEC meeting, and the work of formulating the APEC post-2020 cooperation vision is progressing in an orderly manner.
Malaysia agrees to hold APEC-related meetings by video, but does not rule out the possibility of arranging physical meetings during the informal APEC leaders' meeting at the end of the year.
