Economic Observer Network reporter Rao Xianjun On July 26, Greenfield Holdings (600606.SH) issued the " Indicative Notice that state-owned shareholders intend to transfer part of the company's shares and resume trading through public solicitation of transferees. "
The contents of the announcement show that in order to further deepen the reform of state-owned enterprises, optimize the structural adjustment of state-owned assets, and improve the ownership structure of Greenfield, Shanghai Real Estate (Group) Co., Ltd. (hereinafter referred to as " Shanghai Real Estate ") and Shanghai City Investment (Group) Co., Ltd. (hereinafter referred to as " Shanghai City Investment ") intend to transfer part of the company's shares by agreement through public solicitation of transferees, and the total proportion of shares to be transferred shall not exceed 17.5% of Greenfield's total share capital.
The price of the shares to be transferred this time shall not be lower than the higher of the following two: the arithmetic average of the daily weighted average price of the 30 trading days before the indicative announcement date (July 27, 2020); and the audited net asset value per share of the company in the most recent fiscal year.
At present, there is still no conclusion on the new strategic investors of Greenfield. According to the announcement and public information, it is estimated that the new strategic investors will need to pay about 14 billion yuan to win the 17.5% stake transferred by Greenfield this time.
It is worth noting that after the completion of this share transfer, it is expected that Greenfield still has no controlling shareholder and actual controller, but the control structure may change greatly.
Since its inception, Greenfield Holdings has carried out many institutional and mechanism reforms: from 1992 to 1997, it operated in accordance with market-oriented rules under a purely state-owned system; from 1997 to 2013, it established and continuously improved the joint-stock system of state-owned holding and employee shareholding; from 2013 to 2015, it introduced strategic investors to form a mixed ownership system of cross-shareholding and mutual integration of state-owned and non-public capital; since 2015, it has been listed as a public company.
Greenfield's current reform plan is similar to that of Gree. In December 2019, high-level capital led Zhuhai Mingjun to take over 15% of Gree Electric Appliance (000651.SZ) with 41.662 billion yuan. Gree Group retired as a minority shareholder. After completing the reform, Gree Electric Appliance implemented modern enterprise management methods such as executive incentive plan and no real controller structure.
Shanghai Real Estate and Shanghai City Investment are state-owned enterprise groups wholly owned by Shanghai SASAC. Zhang Yuliang, chairman and president of Greenfield Holdings, said that Greenfield's move is an important measure for Shanghai to promote the comprehensive reform of state-owned enterprises and accelerate the reform of state-owned enterprises in the new stage in accordance with the requirements of the Party Central Committee. It fully shows the new reform ideas adapted to local conditions and tailored to local conditions. By introducing new excellent strategic shareholders to listed companies, support enterprises to further improve the degree of marketization, enhance the freedom of operation and management, and accelerate the full release of reform vitality.
