Is it reasonable for a 3-year-old child to sue the school after being smashed in the college playground?
2020-07-26 05: 01: 11 Source: Legal Daily Author: Wang Sishuo Editor: Wang Sishuo
The playground was smashed and the child was compensated before suing the school
□ Zhao Yifan, correspondent of this newspaper
When 3-year-old Xiaowen was playing on a university playground, he was accidentally hit in the head by Chen Mou of the softball team while throwing the ball.
After Chen's compensation, Xiaowen's father, Mr. Wen, as Xiaowen's legal representative, sued the school to the court, demanding an apology from the school where the playground was located, and paying a total of 20,000 yuan for medical expenses and moral damages.
Recently, after hearing the case, the Haidian District People's Court of Beijing held that the school had set up a protective net in the playground at the time of the incident, and had fulfilled its appropriate security obligations, and Chen had made compensation, according to which the judgment rejected the plaintiff's claim.
Mr. Wen complained that during the summer vacation of 2019, he took Xiaowen to play on the school playground, when the softball team was training on the playground.
In order to avoid the risks, Xiaowen, Mr. Wen and many other children and parents operate in the safe area designated by the softball team.
But then softball team member Chen took off while throwing the ball, causing the softball to fly over the net to the above-mentioned safe area and hit Xiaowen in the back of the head.
Mr. Wen immediately took Xiaowen to the hospital for treatment and was diagnosed with head trauma.
Mr. Wen believes that the facilities of the school stadium do not comply with the relevant safety regulations and do not effectively manage the team and related facilities.
The school's negligence led to the above-mentioned events, which caused Xiaowen to suffer great physical and mental pain, but also brought great pain to his family, for which the school should bear legal responsibility.
In this regard, the school argued that the school had set up a protective net in the playground, and posted management regulations and training notices, informing them that entering the playground must maintain a safe distance from the training site and reminding them to pay attention to their own safety. The plaintiff could not prove that the school had " failed to fulfill its security obligations, " so it did not agree to compensation.
After hearing the case, the court held that the site of the incident was a site open to the public free of charge by the university involved. Although the school has a security obligation for the management of the playground, this security obligation only needs to meet the general duty of care.
At the time of the incident, the school set up a protective net in the playground, which has fulfilled its appropriate safety and security obligations, and Chen Mou also compensated Xiaowen for medical expenses, transportation expenses and other losses of more than 2,000 yuan in accordance with the previous compensation agreement. The two sides agreed to resolve the dispute at one time.
Later, Xiaowen's parents once again claimed compensation from the school, which had no basis in the law, and the court ruled to reject all the plaintiffs' claims.
After the verdict, neither party appealed, and the judgment has now entered into force.
According to Article 37 of China's Tort Liability Law, the school, as the manager of a public place, has the obligation of safety and security; in the case of damage caused by the behavior of a third party, the third party shall bear the liability of tort, while the manager of a public place who fails to fulfill the obligation of safety and security shall bear the corresponding supplementary liability.
The judge said that because, as the manager of a public place, he is most likely to understand the actual situation of the whole place and foresee the possible dangers and damage, so he is most likely to take necessary measures to prevent the occurrence of losses or mitigate the extent of damage, and the cost of avoiding and mitigating damage is the lowest, so the law stipulates that he shall bear the corresponding guarantee obligation to engage in social activities.
In this case, for the unspecified people entering the playground open to the public free of charge, the safety and security obligation of the school should be commensurate with the social activities it is engaged in. Specifically, it should mainly take basic safety measures and have the obligation to inform hidden dangers.
In judicial practice, it is not appropriate to impose excessive safety and security obligations on managers of public places.
If the school has set up a protective net and fulfilled its obligation to inform, it can be concluded that the school is not at fault and should not bear legal responsibility.
In addition, for third-party infringement, even if the administrators of schools and other public places fail to fulfill their safety and security obligations, their liability is also as a supplement to compensation for damages. According to the newly promulgated Civil Code, after assuming supplementary liability, the administrators can also recover compensation from the third party.
Therefore, in such accidents, the victim should not expand the scope of claim after having received compensation from the direct infringer.
