Israel strengthens prevention and control of repeated epidemics
At the beginning of the COVID-19 pneumonia outbreak, Israel's prevention and control measures have achieved remarkable results.
However, with the gradual lifting of prevention and control measures, the number of confirmed cases of COVID-19 pneumonia in Israel has increased significantly recently, and the Israeli government has repeatedly taken urgent measures to strengthen the prevention and control of the epidemic.
On February 28, the first case of COVID-19 pneumonia was confirmed in Israel, so it quickly took measures to close all entry and exit ports, suspend non-essential industries, switch schools to online teaching, restrict public transport and non-essential social activities, block cities with serious epidemics, and jointly maintain prevention and control measures by the military and police.
This series of measures quickly achieved positive results. By mid-May, the new confirmed cases of COVID-19 pneumonia in Israel in one day fell to single digits.
As the epidemic has been brought under control, various prevention and control measures in Israel have been fully unlocked, and since June, the number of new confirmed cases of COVID-19 pneumonia has gradually rebounded.
Especially since the beginning of July, the spread of the epidemic has been accelerating.
In recent days, there have been more than 1,500 new cases per day in Israel for eight days, and as of the time of writing on July 25, there were 916 new cases on that day.
As of July 25, there were 59,745 confirmed cases and 448 deaths in Israel.
Faced with the rapid rebound of the epidemic, the Israeli government has repeatedly taken urgent measures to strengthen the prevention and control of the epidemic.
On July 6, after the number of confirmed cases exceeded 30,000, the Israeli government closed gymnasiums, swimming pools, bars, nightclubs and other public entertainment venues, and introduced a policy of restricting public transport, stipulating that the maximum number of passengers per bus should not exceed 20.
On the 17th, the Israeli government announced a series of new restrictions, including the implementation of the " Kwun Tong " on weekends, stipulating that the " Kwun Tong " will be implemented from 17: 00 every Friday to 5: 00 every Sunday.
During this period, people can go out, but shops, shopping centers, barber shops, beauty salons, libraries, zoos, museums, exhibition halls, swimming pools and tourist attractions will be closed, while basic service places such as supermarkets and pharmacies will remain open.
At the same time, on all dates and periods, gatherings of more than 10 people are prohibited, gyms, studios and other places will be closed, restaurants and cafes are prohibited from eating, and only take-out services are allowed.
At the same time, the Israeli people did not pay enough attention to the seriousness of the epidemic and failed to form joint efforts with the government in fighting the epidemic.
After repeated outbreaks in Israel, many people took to the streets to protest and march because the government's prevention and control measures affected their own economic interests.
On July 11, tens of thousands of people held a demonstration in Tel Aviv, arguing that the anti-epidemic policy affected the economy.
On the evening of the 21st, thousands more protesters gathered in front of Prime Minister Netanyahu's official residence in Jerusalem to protest against Prime Minister Netanyahu's promulgation of prevention and control measures such as banning restaurants and coffee halls without giving corresponding compensation.
In addition, many people do not abide by the regulations of wearing masks and maintaining a safe social distance of two meters when outdoors. In order to avoid being fined by the police for not wearing masks, many people only wear masks on their chin or hang them on their wrists.
During the repeated epidemic, the school was the hardest-hit area for the spread of the COVID-19 virus. According to the reporter's recent visit to this kindergarten, it was found that the teachers and students of the kindergarten did not wear masks as required by the government, nor did they maintain a safe social distance of two meters from each other, laying hidden dangers for a large number of teachers and students infected with the virus.
Professor Elie Waxman, a member of the expert advisory panel of the Israeli National Security Council to combat the epidemic, believes that Israel is moving towards a " dangerous situation, " pointing out that the epidemic prevention and control measures currently taken by Israel are not enough, and all leisure and recreational places and summer schools should be closed to control the further spread of the epidemic.
Waxman said that Israel lacks an overall plan to combat the epidemic. The parliament and government departments should abandon their respective interests as soon as possible, reach agreement on fighting the epidemic, and formulate clear steps including relevant restrictions in different departments.
