At the Banong Zhuokang outpost, platoon commander Yu Wang and a soldier stood guard on duty.
In this place, where the average annual temperature is more than ten degrees below zero, a row of simple barracks stands at the mountain pass. A national flag is flying in the wind not far from the barracks. Soldiers stand guard in the wind every day. At the same time, they need to regularly patrol higher elevations.
The soldiers had to use both hands and feet to climb the steep slope of the rubble.
It was late July, when flowers and plants flourished in low-altitude areas, and in Ba Nong Zhuokang, only the ditch behind the barracks had a relatively dense green.
Gao Peng, a soldier who has been stationed at the outpost for six years, pointed to the ravine and said that this is their back garden. Only in July and August every year can the grass grow slowly. Soon after, it all turns yellow and is covered with snow.
A foot patrol may take about nine hours.
Under the harsh plateau environment, the soldiers stationed here are accompanied by snowy mountains and glaciers all the year round. They also regularly patrol mountain passes at higher elevations.
A few days ago, a patrol composed of eight soldiers, led by instructor Liang Yixin, once again took the patrol road.
Each soldier carried a weight of about 30 jin and headed for the target point early in the morning.
On the way, a soldier rebelled, and his comrades-in-arms rushed to rescue him.
In addition to patrol tasks, the soldiers at the Ba Nong Zhuokang outpost have to conduct tactical and physical training every day.
Time passes, the altitude is constantly rising, the oxygen content is getting lower and lower, and the physical strength is constantly overdrawn. These factors test the will of the patrol members.
They clenched their teeth and persisted, crossing several landslides and several dangerous beaches one after another.
At about 16: 00, it was lunch time for the patrol members. They took out their own dry food and sat on the ground at an altitude of more than 5,700 meters, accompanied by sleet and sleet, to supplement their physical strength with food.
The soldiers at the Banong Zhuokang outpost conducted tactical and physical training.
During the break, they will play cards together, and the losers will do push-ups, which can both entertain and exercise physical fitness.
After a short rest in the cold wind, they climbed to the target point of the patrol, took out the national flag on the mountain pass and took a solemn oath.
Behind them are snow-capped mountains, and in front of them are dozens of kilometers of no man's land. They are the safest guardians of the country.
